The article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama commemorating the 50th anniversary of the Civil Rights Act. The Civil Rights Act was a landmark achievement that transformed our understanding of justice, equality, and democracy in the United States. It helped end the Jim Crow era, banned discrimination in public places, prohibited employment discrimination based on race, color, religion, sex, or national origin, and promoted the integration of schools. The proclamation acknowledges the progress made over the past five decades but also recognizes that the journey towards equality is not complete. It calls upon all Americans to observe the anniversary with programs, ceremonies, and activities that celebrate the accomplishments of the Civil Rights Act and continue to advance civil rights in our time.